\fs29\fsmilli14667 Let's imagine your .pem file is a 
\f4\b secret diary
\f1\b0  that contains all the private keys and passwords to your personal vault (your AWS account).\

\f4\b 1. The "Open Diary" (Bad Permissions)
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls52\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The scenario:
\f1\b0  You have a brand new diary. By default, it's left open on your desk. This is like a .pem file with permissions that are too open.\
\ls52\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The problem:
\f1\b0  Anyone who walks into the room (any user on your computer) can pick up the diary and read all your secrets. A potential thief (a hacker) could copy the information and use it to get into your vault.\
\ls52\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The result:
\f1\b0  When you try to use your private key to open your vault, the security system (the SSH connection) will deny you access. It recognizes that the diary is not secure and could be compromised. It's a security feature designed to protect you. The security system is essentially saying, "I can't let you use this key; it's lying out in the open, and I don't trust it."\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0

\f4\b \cf0 2. The "Secured Diary" (Correct Permissions)
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
