\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 This code snippet is a Python function designed to run in an Amazon Web Services (AWS) Lambda environment. Its job is to find all the EC2 virtual servers that are currently running and get a list of their unique IDs.\
Here's a simple breakdown of what each part does:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls94\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
import boto3: This line brings in the special tool kit, called boto3, that lets your code talk to and control different services within AWS.\
\ls94\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
ec2 = boto3.resource('ec2'): This is like grabbing a specific tool from the kit\'97the one for managing EC2, which are virtual servers.\
\ls94\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
def lambda_handler(event, context):: This is the main starting point of the code. AWS Lambda knows to run the code inside this function when it's triggered.\
\ls94\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
filters = [...]: This part sets up your search criteria. It's telling the program exactly what to look for: instances where the "instance-state-name" is "running."\
\ls94\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
instances = ec2.instances.filter(Filters=filters): This is the action. It uses your search criteria to ask the EC2 service to give you a list of all the virtual servers that match.\
\ls94\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
RunningInstances = []: This creates an empty list, like an empty notebook, where you'll write down the results.\
\ls94\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The for loop: This goes through each item that the search found. For every virtual server, it takes its unique ID and adds it to your notebook (RunningInstances.append). The print line also displays each ID as it's added.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
