\f1\b0 After creating a file with 'touch', you need to open it to write the script. This can be done using a terminal-based text editor. 'vi' is a standard editor available on all Linux machines by default. 'vim' (VI Improved) is an enhanced version that may need to be installed. You can open a file by typing 'vi '. Interestingly, if you use 'vi' or 'vim' on a file that doesn't exist, the editor will create it for you. This raises the question of why 'touch' is needed. The 'touch' command is crucial for automation scripts where you might need to create thousands of files. Using 'vim' would open each file, consuming system resources, whereas 'touch' simply creates them without opening them, which is far more efficient for bulk operations.\
\ls125\ilvl0
