\f1\b0 If you run vim second_shell_script.sh and the file does not exist, vim will open a new buffer and state that it is a 'new file'. You can then start writing in it. This seems to make touch redundant. However, in an automation scenario where you need to create 1000 files, using vim in a script would open 1000 instances of the editor, which is inefficient and can cause problems. Using touch would simply create the 1000 files without opening them, which is the correct approach for such automated tasks.\
