Explanation\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 When writing a shell script, the very first line must be the shebang. Its syntax is a hash and an exclamation mark (#!) followed by the absolute path to the shell interpreter. This line is critical because it defines the execution environment for the script. Different shells (like Bash, Bourne shell, KornShell) have slightly different syntax and features, and the shebang ensures the correct one is used.\
\ls127\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Example: Standard Bash Shebang\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 To start a bash script, the first line written in the file is:\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 #!/bin/bash\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
