\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls129\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The shebang is the very first line in a shell script.\
\ls129\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
It starts with #!.\
\ls129\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
It specifies the absolute path to the shell executable that will interpret the script.\
\ls129\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Common examples include #!/bin/bash, #!/bin/sh, and #!/usr/bin/env bash.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls129\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Explanation\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 When you run a shell script, the operating system's kernel needs to know which program should execute the commands within it. The shebang line provides this information. For example, #!/bin/bash tells the system to use the bash executable located in the /bin directory. Different shells like bash, ksh, sh, and dash exist, and they are the executables that process the script. The shebang ensures that the correct interpreter is used, which is important because different shells can have slightly different syntax.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0

\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \cf0 6. Shell Executables (bash, ksh, sh, dash)
