\ls130\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Different shell executables include bash, ksh, sh, and dash.\
\ls130\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
They have minor syntax differences. For example, a for loop is written differently in bash and ksh.\
\ls130\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
bash is the most common and recommended shell for scripting today.\
\ls130\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
ksh is considered obsolete and is not widely used anymore.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls130\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Explanation\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 These executables are the interpreters for shell scripts. bash (Bourne Again Shell) is the most widely used and is recommended for modern scripting due to its features and ease of use. ksh (KornShell) is older and now considered largely obsolete, with different syntax for constructs like for loops. sh (Bourne Shell) and dash (Debian Almquist Shell) are other variants. It's important to specify the correct executable in the shebang to avoid syntax errors.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0

\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \cf0 7. Difference Between /bin/sh and /bin/bash
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls131\ilvl0
\f4\b\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
