\ls131\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
This is a common interview question.\
\ls131\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Previously, /bin/sh was often a symbolic link to /bin/bash, making them effectively the same on many systems.\
\ls131\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Modern operating systems (e.g., Ubuntu) now link /bin/sh to /bin/dash by default.\
\ls131\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Scripts with bash-specific features will fail if run with dash.\
\ls131\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Best practice: Always use the explicit shebang #!/bin/bash for bash scripts to avoid compatibility issues.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls131\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Explanation\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 Historically, /bin/sh was often a symbolic link to /bin/bash on many Linux systems. This meant that even if a script specified #!/bin/sh, it would be executed by bash. However, in recent years, some operating systems like Ubuntu have changed this behavior. They now link /bin/sh to /bin/dash, a different shell. If you write a script with bash-specific syntax but use the #!/bin/sh shebang, it will fail on these systems because dash does not understand the bash syntax. Therefore, to ensure portability and correctness, you should always use #!/bin/bash for scripts written in bash.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0

