Explanation\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 A script can be executed using sh <filename> or ./<filename>. However, a newly created file does not have execute permissions by default, leading to a 'Permission denied' error. The chmod (change mode) command is used to grant these permissions. Permissions in Linux are categorized for the user (owner), the group, and others. They are often represented by numbers: 4 for read, 2 for write, and 1 for execute. These numbers are summed for combined permissions (e.g., 7 for read+write+execute). chmod 777 <filename> grants read, write, and execute permissions to everyone, allowing the script to be run.\
\ls136\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Granting Full Permissions to a File\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 chmod 777 my_script.sh\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls136\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
This command grants execute permissions. The first '7' gives read (4), write (2), and execute (1) permissions to the file's owner. The second '7' gives the same permissions to the group. The third '7' gives the same permissions to all other users.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls136\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Granting Only Read Permissions\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 chmod 444 xyz\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls136\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
This command grants only read permission (4) to the user, group, and others for the file named 'xyz'.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0

