\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The 'chmod' command is used to change the permissions of a file.\
\ls145\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Permissions are represented numerically: 4 for read, 2 for write, and 1 for execute.\
\ls145\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
These numbers are combined to set permissions for three categories of users: the owner (user), the group, and others.\
\ls145\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A 'chmod 777' command grants read, write, and execute permissions to everyone.\
\ls145\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A 'chmod 770' command grants full permissions to the owner and group but denies all permissions to others.\
\ls145\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
