\ls145\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Explanation\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 The permission system in Linux is based on a numeric formula where 4 stands for read, 2 for write, and 1 for execute. The sum of these numbers determines the level of access. For example, 7 (4+2+1) grants full read, write, and execute permissions. The 'chmod' command applies these permissions to the user, group, and others. For instance, 'chmod 777 sample_shell_script.sh' makes the script readable, writable, and executable by all users.\
