\ls148\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
To improve efficiency, he wrote a shell script to automate the diagnosis and stores in git. This script could log into a specific machine (e.g., the 9999th VM) and check its CPU and memory status.\
\ls148\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
John then enhanced the script to run automatically on a schedule (e.g., once a day). The script would log into all 10,000 VMs, check their health, and send an email notification summarizing the status, such as '10 machines seem suspicious, with 5 having memory issues and 5 having CPU issues'.\
\ls148\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
This automation saves significant manual effort and allows for proactive monitoring. When asked why not use existing tools, a valid reason is that a custom script can be tailored to fetch specific parameters not available in standard tools.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \u8232 \'a0\
