\f0\b0\fs24 \cf3 As a 
\f2\b Senior Platform Engineer
\f0\b0 , you are expected to solve scaling problems. Use these scenarios to showcase your expertise.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf3 Scenario A: Automating Resource Health Checks\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf3 Question:
\f0\b0  
\f3\i \cf3 \strokec3 "How have you used shell scripting to manage a large-scale environment?"
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls164\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Situation:
\f0\b0  I was responsible for monitoring the health of over 10,000 Linux VMs. Manually checking CPU and memory usage when developers reported "slowness" was impossible.\
\ls164\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Task:
\f0\b0  I needed a way to proactively identify which nodes were under stress without logging into them one by one.\
\ls164\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Action:
\f0\b0  I wrote a shell script that utilized \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 nproc\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  (CPU count) and \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 free -m\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  (Memory status). I combined these with the \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 top -b -n 1\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  command to capture a snapshot of the highest-consuming processes. I then scheduled this script as a 
\f2\b Cron Job
\f0\b0  to run daily.\
\ls164\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Result:
\f0\b0  The script automatically identified the top 10 "suspicious" nodes and emailed a report to the team. This allowed us to fix memory leaks before they caused system outages.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf3 \strokec3 Scenario B: Standardizing Deployment Pipelines\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf3 Question:
\f0\b0  
\f3\i \cf3 \strokec3 "Tell me about a time a script failed in production and how you fixed it."
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls165\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Situation:
\f0\b0  We had a legacy script using \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 #!/bin/sh\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  that started failing after we migrated our build agents to a newer version of Ubuntu.\
\ls165\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Task:
\f0\b0  I had to identify why the script, which worked for years, was suddenly throwing "syntax errors" on simple \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 if\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  statements.\
\ls165\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Action:
\f0\b0  I discovered that on the new OS, \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 /bin/sh\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  was linked to \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 dash\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  instead of \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 bash\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 . The script used bash-specific syntax. I performed a global search-and-replace to update the shebang to \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 #!/bin/bash\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  and used \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 chmod 755\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  to ensure proper execution permissions across the CI/CD pipeline.\
\ls165\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Result:
\f0\b0  The pipeline was restored, and I implemented a linting step (using \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 shellcheck\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ) in our Git hooks to ensure all future scripts used the correct shebang and syntax.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

