Analogy:
\f1\b0  The pipe command is like a conveyor belt in a factory. It takes the output from one machine and immediately sends it as input to the next machine, allowing you to chain a series of operations together.\
\ls214\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Explanation:
\f1\b0  In shell scripting, the pipe | command is used to pass the output of one command as the input to another command. This is incredibly powerful for chaining commands together to perform complex tasks. For example, ps aux | grep 'apache' takes the full list of all running processes (ps aux) and sends it to the grep command, which then filters that list to show only the lines that contain the word "apache."\
