awk: A powerful text-processing tool that can be used to filter, format, and manipulate text data. It's often used with grep to pull out specific columns of data from a list of processes.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0

\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \cf0 Best Practices: set -e and set -o pipefail
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls216\ilvl0
\f4\b\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy:
\f1\b0  These are like safety rules for your script.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls216\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
set -e: This is the "no tolerance for failure" rule. It says that if any command in the script fails, the entire script should stop immediately, like pulling an emergency brake. This prevents a failed command from causing unexpected and potentially disastrous results later on.\
\ls216\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
set -o pipefail: This rule is a bit more specific. It's like having a rule for your conveyor belt (the pipe command). It says, "If any part of the conveyor belt jams, the entire assembly line should be considered a failure." Without this, a command in the middle of a pipe could fail, but the script would keep going, thinking everything is fine.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls216\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Explanation:
\f1\b0  These commands are crucial for writing robust and reliable scripts. set -e ensures that the script exits immediately if a command fails, while set -o pipefail ensures that a piped command's exit status is considered a failure if any command in the pipe fails, not just the last one.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 You can learn more about some of these concepts in this video on shell scripting for DevOps. The video is relevant because it covers several of the topics you listed, such as debugging with set -x, ps and grep, the pipe command, and best practices like set -e and set -o pipefail.\
