\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf3 1. What is the difference between \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 sh script.sh\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  and \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 ./script.sh\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf3 Answer:
\f0\b0  * 
\f2\b \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 sh script.sh
\f0\b0 \cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 : You are explicitly calling the shell interpreter to run the file. It does 
\f2\b not
\f0\b0  require the file to have execute permissions (\cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 +x\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ).\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls217\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf10 \cb11 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec10 ./script.sh
\f0\b0 \cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 : The system looks at the 
\f2\b Shebang
\f0\b0  (\cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 #!\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ) line to decide which interpreter to use. This method 
\f2\b requires
\f0\b0  the file to have execute permissions.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf3 \strokec3 2. When would you use \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 ps -ef\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  vs \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 grep\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf3 Answer:
\f0\b0  \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 ps -ef\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  lists every single process running on the system. Because this list is huge, we use a "pipe" (\cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 |\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ) to send that data to \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 grep\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  to filter for a specific process (e.g., \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 ps -ef | grep amazon\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf3 3. Explain the command \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 df -h\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf3 Answer:
\f0\b0  The \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 df\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  command stands for "disk free." The \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 -h\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  flag stands for "human-readable," which converts bytes into megabytes (M) and gigabytes (G), making it easier for a DevOps engineer to quickly assess if a volume is nearly full.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf3 4. What are the common \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 vi/vim\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  modes you use?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf3 Answer:
\f0\b0  * 
\f2\b Command Mode
\f0\b0 : The default mode for navigating and deleting text.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls218\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Insert Mode (\cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 i\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 )
\f0\b0 : For typing content.\
\ls218\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Extended Command Mode (\cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 :\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 )
\f0\b0 : For saving (\cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 :w\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ), quitting (\cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 :q\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ), or both (\cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 :wq!\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ).\
