\fs28 \cf3 Scenario: Investigating Performance Bottlenecks\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf3 Question:
\f0\b0  
\f3\i \cf3 \strokec3 "A developer reports that their application on a specific VM is sluggish. How do you diagnose this using only the terminal?"
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls219\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Situation:
\f0\b0  I received a ticket stating that an application server in the staging environment was unresponsive during a load test.\
\ls219\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Task:
\f0\b0  I needed to identify whether the bottleneck was CPU, Memory, or a specific runaway process.\
\ls219\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Action:
\f0\b0  I logged into the VM via SSH and immediately ran the \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 top\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  command to get a real-time view of system resource consumption. I noticed that the CPU load was high. I then used \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 nproc\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  to verify the total CPU count to see if the load average was exceeding the available cores. Finally, I used \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 ps -ef | grep <app-name>\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  to find the specific Process ID (PID) of the application to see if it was in a "zombie" or "stuck" state.\
\ls219\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Result:
\f0\b0  I identified a specific thread that was consuming 95% of a single core. I provided the PID and the logs to the developer, who found a logic loop in their code. We killed the process, restarted the service, and the system returned to normal.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

