\f2\b\fs36 \cf3 \strokec3 1. The Foundation: Shebang & Interpreters\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls220\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 The Concept:
\f0\b0  The Shebang (\cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 #!\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ) tells the OS which "engine" to use. \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 bash\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  is the standard for DevOps because it is feature-rich.\
\ls220\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Interview Q:
\f0\b0  
\f3\i "What happens if you omit the shebang line?"
\f0\i0 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls220\ilvl1
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f10 \uc0\u9702 
\f2 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Answer:
\f0\b0  The script will execute using the default shell of the user who runs it (often \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 sh\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  or \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 dash\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ). This can cause "Syntax Error" if you used Bash-specific features like arrays or double brackets.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls220\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 STAR Scenario:
\f0\b0 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls220\ilvl1
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f10 \uc0\u9702 
\f2 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 S:
\f0\b0  A legacy deployment script was failing on our new Ubuntu servers.\
\ls220\ilvl1
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f10 \uc0\u9702 
\f2 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 T:
\f0\b0  I had to identify why a script that worked for years was suddenly breaking.\
\ls220\ilvl1
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f10 \uc0\u9702 
\f2 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 A:
\f0\b0  I checked the shebang and saw \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 #!/bin/sh\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 . On the new OS, \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 sh\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  was linked to \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 dash\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 , which didn't support the script's bash-specific loops. I updated the shebang to \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 #!/bin/bash\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 .\
\ls220\ilvl1
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f10 \uc0\u9702 
\f2 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 R:
\f0\b0  The script immediately worked, and I standardized all repository scripts to use explicit bash paths.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf3 \strokec3 2. File Permissions & Execution\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls221\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 The Concept:
\f0\b0  Linux is "Secure by Default." A script isn't a program until you give it "Execute" (\cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 x\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ) permissions.\
\ls221\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Interview Q:
\f0\b0  
\f3\i "How do you make a script executable without giving everyone full access (777)?"
\f0\i0 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls221\ilvl1
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f10 \uc0\u9702 
\f2 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Answer:
\f0\b0  Use \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 chmod 755 script.sh\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  (Owner has full access, others can only read/execute) or \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 chmod +x script.sh\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf3 \strokec3 3. Automation vs. Manual (Touch vs. Vim)\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls222\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 The Concept:
\f0\b0  As a Senior Engineer, you don't "open" files to create them. You use commands that work in the background.\
\ls222\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Interview Q:
\f0\b0  
\f3\i "Why is \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 touch\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  better than \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 vi\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  for creating 100 files in a script?"
\f0\i0 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls222\ilvl1
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f10 \uc0\u9702 
\f2 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 Answer:
\f0\b0  \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 touch\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  is non-interactive. \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 vi\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  opens a buffer in the terminal which would hang a script or crash the memory if looped 100 times.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls222\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 STAR Scenario:
\f0\b0 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls222\ilvl1
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f10 \uc0\u9702 
\f2 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 S:
\f0\b0  We needed to generate dummy log files to test our log-rotation policy.\
\ls222\ilvl1
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f10 \uc0\u9702 
\f2 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 T:
\f0\b0  I needed to create 500 files with specific timestamps.\
\ls222\ilvl1
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f10 \uc0\u9702 
\f2 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 A:
\f0\b0  I wrote a one-liner: \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 for i in \{1..500\}; do touch "log_$i.txt"; done\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 .\
\ls222\ilvl1
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	
\f10 \uc0\u9702 
\f2 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 R:
\f0\b0  I created the test environment in seconds rather than minutes, allowing the team to finish the rotation testing ahead of schedule.\
