\f4\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 The "Node Health" Script Template\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf3 \strokec3 #!/bin/bash\
\
#################################################################\
# Author: Sunil Kumar Gowda\
# Date: 12-May-2026\
# Version: v1\
#\
# This script outputs the Node Health (CPU, Memory, Disk)\
#################################################################\
\
set -e # Exit the script if a command fails\
set -o pipefail # Capture errors in piped commands\
\
echo "------------------- CPU COUNT -------------------"\
nproc\
\
echo "------------------ MEMORY USAGE -----------------"\
free -m\
\
echo "------------------- DISK USAGE ------------------"\
df -h\
\
echo "----------------- TOP PROCESSES -----------------"\
top -b -n 1 | head -n 10\
\
echo "----------------- FILTERED PROCESSES ------------"\
ps -ef | grep "amazon" | awk '\{print $2\}' # Extracts PIDs of amazon-related tasks\
\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f4\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Technical Q&A for this Script\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 1. Why did you use 
\f11\fs30\fsmilli15210 \strokec2 set -e
\f4\fs28 \strokec2  at the top?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Answer:
\f1\b0 \strokec2  This is a best practice for "Fail Fast" in DevOps. If any command in the script fails, the script stops immediately. This prevents a "snowball effect" where one error leads to a major system failure down the line.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f4\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 2. What is the difference between 
\f11\fs30\fsmilli15210 \strokec2 free -m
\f4\fs28 \strokec2  and 
\f11\fs30\fsmilli15210 \strokec2 free -g
\f4\fs28 \strokec2 ?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Answer:
\f1\b0 \strokec2  
\f12\fs26 \strokec2 -m
\f1\fs24 \strokec2  shows the memory in 
\f4\b \strokec2 Megabytes
\f1\b0 \strokec2 , and 
\f12\fs26 \strokec2 -g
\f1\fs24 \strokec2  shows it in 
\f4\b \strokec2 Gigabytes
\f1\b0 \strokec2 . In an interview, I\'92d mention that I use 
\f12\fs26 \strokec2 -m
\f1\fs24 \strokec2  for smaller instances (like 
\f12\fs26 \strokec2 t2.micro
\f1\fs24 \strokec2 ) and 
\f12\fs26 \strokec2 -g
\f1\fs24 \strokec2  for enterprise-grade servers to get a clearer picture of available resources.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f4\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 3. How does 
\f11\fs30\fsmilli15210 \strokec2 top -b -n 1 | head -n 10
\f4\fs28 \strokec2  work?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Answer:
\f1\b0 \strokec2  
\f12\fs26 \strokec2 top
\f1\fs24 \strokec2  is usually interactive (it keeps running). The 
\f12\fs26 \strokec2 -b
\f1\fs24 \strokec2  (batch mode) and 
\f12\fs26 \strokec2 -n 1
\f1\fs24 \strokec2  (number of iterations) allow it to run once and exit, making it script-friendly. I then pipe it to 
\f12\fs26 \strokec2 head
\f1\fs24 \strokec2  to only see the top 10 most resource-hungry processes.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

