\ls227\ilvl0
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Commonly Used Shell Commands: The interviewer's question about commonly used shell commands aims to understand your practical, day-to-day experience with shell scripting.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Write a shell script to list all processes: This question assesses whether you regularly work on Linux machines and are familiar with basic process management.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Write a script to print only errors from a remote log file: This question tests your ability to handle a common real-world scenario: fetching and filtering logs from a remote source like Google Storage or an S3 bucket.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Using curl, pipe, and grep to filter log files: This knowledge point explains how to use a combination of curl, pipe, and grep commands to retrieve and filter specific information from a log file, especially a large one hosted at a URL.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Shell Script to Print Numbers Divisible by 3 and 5, but Not 15: This is a common type of interview question that tests your ability to use loops and conditional logic in shell scripting. It represents a category of questions (e.g., print even/odd numbers, prime numbers, or numbers divisible by specific factors) where the goal is to print numbers within a specified range (e.g., 1 to 100) that meet certain divisibility criteria.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	6	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Script to Count Character Occurrences in a String: This knowledge point covers writing a shell script to count the number of times a specific character appears in a given string, using 'Mississippi' and the character 's' as an example.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	7	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Debugging in a Shell Script: A simple method to enable debug mode for troubleshooting a shell script.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	8	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Crontab in Linux: crontab is a Linux utility used to schedule the automatic execution of commands or scripts at specified times or intervals.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	9	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Opening a File in Read-Only Mode: How to open a file for viewing in a way that prevents any modifications.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	10	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Difference between Soft and Hard Link: In Linux, there are two types of links for files: soft links and hard links. They differ in how they reference the original file and their behavior when the original file is deleted.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	11	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Difference between Break and Continue Statements in a Loop: The break and continue statements are used within loops to alter their execution flow. break terminates the entire loop, while continue skips the current iteration and proceeds to the next one.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	12	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Disadvantages of Shell Scripting: Shell scripting has several disadvantages, a primary one being that it is not statically typed, which can lead to issues with undeclared variables.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	13	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Different Kinds of Loops in Shell Scripting: Like other programming languages, shell scripting supports various types of loops to perform iterative tasks, including for loops, while loops, and do while loops.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	14	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Bash: Dynamically or Statically Typed?: By default, Bash is a dynamically typed language.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	15	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Networking Troubleshooting Tools: Linux offers command-line tools for diagnosing network issues, with traceroute and tracepath being notable examples.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	16	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
How to Sort a List of Names in a File: The most straightforward method to sort content in a file in Linux is by using the native sort command.\
\ls227\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	17	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
How to Manage Huge Log Files: The standard and efficient way to manage large log files on a Linux system is by using the logrotate utility.\
