\ls229\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Explanation\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 To list all processes, you can use the ps -ef command. An interviewer might extend this question by asking you to print only the process ID (PID). The output of ps -ef shows information in columns, with the PID being in the second column. To extract just this column, you can pipe the output to the awk command. awk can process text line by line and field by field. By using awk '\{print $2\}', you are telling it to print the second field (column) of every line, which corresponds to the process ID.\
\ls229\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Command to list all running processes\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 ps -ef\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls229\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
This command lists all the processes currently running on the system in full format.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls229\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Command to list only the process IDs (PIDs) of all running processes\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 ps -ef | awk '\{print $2\}'\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls229\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The output of ps -ef is piped to the awk command.\
\ls229\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
awk processes the output, and '\{print $2\}' instructs it to print only the second column, which is the Process ID.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \'a0\
\ls229\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
