\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls231\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
curl retrieves the entire content of the remote file.\
\ls231\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The pipe (|) command sends the output of curl as input to grep.\
\ls231\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
grep filters this input to find and display only lines containing a specific pattern.\
\ls231\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
This combination is essential for efficiently filtering large remote files without downloading them entirely first.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls231\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Explanation\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 The process involves three commands. First, curl is used to retrieve the entire content of the log file from its URL. Second, the pipe command (|) is used to send the output of the curl command as input to the grep command. This is crucial because without the pipe, the commands would not be linked, and grep would not receive the curl output. Third, grep filters this input to find and display only the lines containing a specific pattern, such as 'trace' or 'error'. This allows you to isolate relevant log entries from a potentially massive file without manually reading through it.\
\ls231\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Filtering Trace and Error Logs from a Remote Log File\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 \'a0\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls231\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \'a0\
