\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\'a0\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 To get only the 'trace' logs from a log file at a given URL, the command is:\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 '''\
curl [url_of_the_file] | grep t-r-a-c-a\
'''\uc0\u8232 \'a0\
\
To get the 'error' logs, the command would be:\
'''\
curl [url_of_the_file] | grep error\
'''\uc0\u8232 \'a0\
\
\uc0\u8232 \'a0\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls233\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
curl retrieves the entire log file from the specified URL.\
\ls233\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The pipe (|) takes the output of curl and sends it as the input for the grep command.\
\ls233\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
grep t-r-a-c-a or grep error then filters this input, printing only the lines that contain the specified string ('t-r-a-c-a' or 'error').\
\ls233\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
This combination allows for efficient filtering of large log files directly from the command line.\
