\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \cf0 10. Difference between Soft and Hard Link
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls245\ilvl0
\f4\b\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Key Points
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls245\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A hard link is an additional directory entry that points directly to the same underlying data (inode) as the original file.\
\ls245\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
If the original file is deleted, the hard link still exists, and the data persists as long as at least one hard link to it remains.\
\ls245\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A soft link (or symbolic link) is a reference or shortcut to a file, containing the path to the original file.\
\ls245\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
If the original file is deleted, the soft link becomes broken (a dangling pointer) and is no longer usable.\
\ls245\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The command to create a link is ln.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls245\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Explanation\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 When a file is created, it is saved in memory or on disk. Instead of creating a full copy of a file to reuse it, you can use links. A hard link acts as a mirror or a direct reference to the file's content. If the original file is deleted, the hard link still exists with the content intact, serving as a backup, because it points to the same data on disk. A soft link, however, is a pointer or a shortcut to the original file's path. If the original file is deleted, the soft link becomes a broken link and is no longer usable.\
\ls245\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Hard Link for File Backup\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 If you have a 'secret file' with sensitive information that should not be deleted, you can create a hard link to it. The hard link will create an additional reference to the file's data. If the original 'secret file' is accidentally deleted from the memory, the hard link copy will still exist, preserving the information.\
\ls245\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Soft Link for Command Alias\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 On a system with Python 3 installed, you will often find a python3 file. You can create a soft link named python that points to python3. This allows you to run scripts by simply typing python instead of python3. The Linux terminal will redirect the command to python3. However, if you delete the original python3 file, the python soft link will no longer work.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0

\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \cf0 11. Difference between Break and Continue Statements in a Loop
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls246\ilvl0
\f4\b\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Key Points
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls246\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Break: Exits the loop's execution completely.\
\ls246\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Continue: Skips the current iteration and moves to the next one. It can be understood as 'skip this and continue the next'.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls246\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Explanation\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 The terms themselves are self-explanatory. 'Break' means to stop the execution of the loop entirely. 'Continue' implies skipping the remainder of the current iteration under a special condition and moving on to the next iteration of the loop. It can be understood as 'skip this and continue the next'.\
\ls246\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Continue Statement Example\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 Consider a for loop that checks if numbers are divisible by 3 or 5. If a number is divisible by both 3 and 5 (i.e., a multiple of 15), you can use the continue statement to ignore that number and proceed to the next iteration of the loop.\
\ls246\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Break Statement Example\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 Imagine you have a list of a hundred students stored in a CSV or Excel file. You need to loop through the names and print them. If the requirement is to stop the execution as soon as a student named 'abhishek' is found, you use a break statement. If 'abhishek' is the 10th student, the loop will print the first nine students, then 'abhishek', and then terminate, not processing the remaining students.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0

