\f1\b0 In a dynamically typed language like Bash or Python, you can assign a value to a variable without pre-defining its data type. In contrast, a statically typed language like Go requires you to declare a variable's type (e.g., var x is a string). If you then try to assign a value of a different type (e.g., an integer), the interpreter will throw an error. This type of strict checking does not happen by default in shell scripting.\
