\f2\b\fs36 \cf3 \strokec3 2. Technical Interview Q&A\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf3 Q1: Why would you use \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 set -x\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  in a shell script?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf3 Answer:
\f0\b0  \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 set -x\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  is the "debug mode." It prints every command before executing it. This is critical for troubleshooting complex scripts where you need to see exactly which variable or path is causing a failure in a production environment.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf3 Q2: How do you extract the Process ID (PID) of a specific application automatically?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf3 Answer:
\f0\b0  I would use \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 ps -ef | grep "app_name" | awk '\{print $2\}'\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 . \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 ps\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  lists the processes, \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 grep\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  finds the specific one, and \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 awk\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  isolates the second column, which is the PID.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf3 Q3: What is the benefit of \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 top -b -n 1\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  over just running \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 top\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf3 Answer:
\f0\b0  \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 top\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  is interactive and never stops. In a script, I use \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 -b\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  (batch mode) and \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 -n 1\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  (run once) so the script can capture a snapshot of CPU usage and then move on to the next task without getting "stuck."\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf3 Q4: How do you handle a "Disk Full" issue using automation?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf3 Answer:
\f0\b0  I write a script that runs \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 df -h\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 . I pipe that to \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 awk\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  to check the percentage column. If it exceeds 90%, the script can trigger an action, like deleting old \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 /tmp\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  files or sending an alert to a Slack channel.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
