\f2\b\fs28 \cf3 Scenario 1: Automated Health Monitoring (Disk/RAM)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf3 Question:
\f0\b0  
\f3\i \cf3 \strokec3 "How do you handle proactive system maintenance?"
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls266\ilvl0\cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\b S (Situation):
\f0\b0  Our production database servers were occasionally crashing due to hidden log files filling up the disk space. \uc0\u8232 \
\ls266\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\b T (Task):
\f0\b0  I needed to create an automated system that monitored disk and RAM usage every hour and alerted the team before a crash occurred. \uc0\u8232 \
\ls266\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 A (Action):
\f0\b0  I wrote a bash script using \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 df -h\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  and \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 free -m\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 . I used 
\f2\b conditional statements
\f0\b0  (\cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 if-else\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ) to check if disk usage exceeded 90%. I integrated the \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 logger\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  command to send status updates to \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 /var/logs/messages\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  for auditing. I then scheduled the script as a 
\f2\b Crontab
\f0\b0  job to run every hour. \uc0\u8232 \
\ls266\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 R (Result):
\f0\b0  We reduced critical "Disk Full" outages by 100%. The team now receives an 
\f2\b Alert Email
\f0\b0  whenever space is low, allowing us to clear logs proactively. \uc0\u8232 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf3 \strokec3 Scenario 2: Troubleshooting a Faulty Script\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf3 Question:
\f0\b0  
\f3\i \cf3 \strokec3 "Tell me about a time you had to debug a complex automation script."
\f0\i0 \cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls267\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 S (Situation):
\f0\b0  A deployment script I inherited was failing silently on certain servers, leaving the application in a partially updated state.\
\ls267\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 T (Task):
\f0\b0  I had to identify the exact line where the failure occurred and ensure the script stopped immediately on errors.\
\ls267\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 \uc0\u8232 
\f2\b A (Action):
\f0\b0  I modified the script by adding \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 set -x\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  to enable 
\f2\b debug mode
\f0\b0 , which printed every command to the terminal as it ran. I also added \cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 set -e\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3  at the top of the script to ensure it would 
\f2\b exit immediately
\f0\b0  if any command failed, preventing corrupted deployments. \uc0\u8232 \
\ls267\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 R (Result):
\f0\b0  I quickly identified that a directory path was incorrectly defined in an associative array. After fixing the variable and implementing error-handling exit codes (\cf10 \cb11 \strokec10 $?\cf3 \cb1 \strokec3 ), the deployment success rate reached 100%. \uc0\u8232 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
