\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 \ul Gemini AI\ulnone :\uc0\u8232 That's a great slide that gets right to the core of how computers work. It breaks down the relationship between software, the operating system, and hardware in a really clear way.\u8232 Let's use a restaurant analogy to make sense of it.\u8232 Imagine a restaurant.\u8232 The 
\f4\b Hardware
\f1\b0  is the kitchen. It has all the physical equipment: the oven, the stove, the cutting boards, and the refrigerators. These are like your computer's CPU, RAM, and I/O (Input/Output) devices. Without them, you can't cook anything.\uc0\u8232 The 
\f4\b Software
\f1\b0  is the food you want to cook. This includes things like your favorite video game, a word processor like Microsoft Word, or even a build tool like Jenkins. They are the instructions for what you want the computer to do.\uc0\u8232 The 
\f4\b Operating System
\f1\b0  (OS) is the head chef. The chef knows exactly how to use all the equipment in the kitchen. When you, the user, want to cook something (run a program), you don't go directly to the oven. Instead, you give your recipe (the software) to the head chef. The chef then figures out how to use the oven, the stove, and all the other tools to make your meal. The OS manages the hardware so that the software can run properly, without you having to know all the technical details of the kitchen itself.\uc0\u8232 The diagram on the right shows a user (USER) interacting with an application (APP). This is like a customer giving an order to a waiter. The app talks to the operating system (Windows, in this example), which then gives instructions to the hardware (CPU, RAM, I/O) to fulfill the request. This is happening on your specific computer, in this case a Dell, which is just one brand of kitchen. This whole system is what allows you to play games, write code, or do anything else on your computer.\u8232 So, in short:\
