Communication
\f1\b0 : An operating system is essential because it establishes the communication link. Without it, software wouldn't know how to interact with the CPU, RAM, or other hardware.
\f4\b \
\ls279\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
User Requests
\f1\b0 : When you, as a user, run a program, your request travels from the application to the OS. The OS then translates that request into instructions that the hardware can understand and execute. The results of the execution travel back through the same path to you.
\f4\b \
\ls279\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
System Libraries
\f1\b0 : These are collections of pre-written, reusable code. Think of them as a toolbox that comes with the operating system. When a program needs to perform a common task, like opening a file or sending data over a network, it doesn't have to write the code from scratch. It can simply call a function from a system library. These libraries can differ between operating systems or even different versions of the same OS, which is why software might behave differently on, say, Debian and CentOS.
\f4\b \
\ls279\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
