Explanation:
\f1\b0  An operating system (OS) is the foundational software that manages all the hardware and software resources on a computer. It acts as an intermediary, handling requests from applications and translating them into instructions for the hardware. System libraries are integral parts of the OS.\
\ls279\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy:
\f1\b0  The operating system is the 
\f4\b traffic controller
\f1\b0  for a city.\
\pard\tx1660\tx2160\pardeftab720\li2160\fi-2160\partightenfactor0
\ls279\ilvl2
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The hardware (CPU, memory, disk):
\f1\b0  The city's infrastructure\'97the roads, bridges, and buildings.\
\ls279\ilvl2
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Applications (web browser, text editor):
\f1\b0  The cars and buses traveling through the city.\
\ls279\ilvl2
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The operating system:
\f1\b0  The traffic controller who directs all the vehicles (applications) to their destinations (hardware resources) efficiently and safely, making sure there are no collisions. A user's request (e.g., "save a file") is like a vehicle requesting a path, and the OS manages the entire journey from the application to the hard drive.\
