Explanation:
\f1\b0  The "AI Suggestion" reframes the lesson's core as understanding the Linux Kernel. It suggests that by learning to use basic command-line tools like ps (for processes) and free (for memory), a learner is indirectly interacting with the kernel and can grasp its functions. The kernel is the central component of the OS, responsible for managing the hardware and facilitating communication.\
\ls279\ilvl2
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy:
\f1\b0  The Linux kernel is the 
\f4\b engine of a car
\f1\b0 . The car itself is the operating system. You don't see the engine directly, but when you press the gas pedal (run a process) or check the fuel gauge (check memory), you are directly interacting with and observing the work of the engine.\
\ls279\ilvl2
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Example:
\f1\b0  When a user types ps aux in the terminal, the command-line tool sends a request to the Linux kernel. The kernel's job is to read its internal data structures, get a list of all the running processes, and send that information back to the ps command, which then displays it to the user. The free command works similarly for memory.\
