\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	9	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Shell Scripting for GitHub API Access: This knowledge point covers how to use shell scripting to interact with the GitHub API, specifically to list users who have access to a repository. It includes prerequisites, environment variable setup, command line arguments, permissions, and the use of jq for JSON parsing.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	10	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Version Control System (VCS): A Version Control System (VCS) is a tool that helps manage changes to source code over time, allowing multiple developers to collaborate, track changes, and revert to previous versions when necessary. It solves two major problems: sharing code among developers and maintaining multiple versions of code.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	11	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Centralized vs Distributed Version Control Systems: Centralized Version Control Systems (CVCS) like SVN and CVS rely on a single central server for code management, while Distributed Version Control Systems (DVCS) like Git allow multiple copies of the repository, enabling better collaboration and resilience against server failures.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	12	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Fork in Distributed Version Control Systems: A fork is a complete copy of the original repository, allowing developers to work independently and maintain their own versions. Forking is a key feature in distributed systems like Git, enhancing collaboration and code safety.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	13	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Difference Between Git and GitHub: Git is an open-source distributed version control system for tracking changes in source code, while GitHub is a platform built on top of Git that adds usability features such as issue tracking, code review, project management, and collaboration tools.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	14	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Basic Git Commands and Lifecycle: The basic lifecycle of using Git involves initializing a repository, adding files, committing changes, and pushing updates. Essential commands include git init, git add, git commit, and git push.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	15	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git Internal Structure: .git Folder: The .git folder is a hidden directory created when initializing a Git repository. It contains essential components like objects, refs, and hooks, which are used for tracking changes, managing references, and automating actions.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	16	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git Configuration and .git Folder: Git configuration is used to set up credentials, secrets, TLS, and certificates for secure repositories. The .git folder is the core of a Git repository, storing all objects, commits, and project history in an encrypted or compressed way.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	17	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Basic Git Commands: git status, git add, git diff, git commit, git log, git reset: Git provides commands to manage file tracking, view changes, commit versions, and revert to previous states. These commands are essential for version control and collaboration.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	18	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Distributed Version Control and Sharing Code: Git is a distributed version control system, allowing code sharing and collaboration via platforms like GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket, or self-hosted solutions.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	19	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git Branching Strategy: Branching strategy is crucial for managing releases, features, and collaboration in software development. Branches allow separation of new or breaking changes from stable code, ensuring prompt and safe releases.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	20	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Upcoming Topics and Homework: Future classes will cover GitHub in detail, including user management, organizations, issues, pull requests, CICD, project management, and security features. Additional git commands and interview questions will also be discussed.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	21	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Course Structure and Timeline: The DevOps course runs from day 0 to day 45, with day 10 focusing on Git and branching strategies. Previous videos cover foundational topics, and students are encouraged to watch them for better understanding.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	22	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Feature Branches: Feature branches are created for developing new features in a codebase, especially when the feature is large or may introduce breaking changes. Developers collaborate on these branches, and once confident, merge them back into the main or master branch.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	23	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Master/Main Branch: The master or main branch is the central branch in a repository, containing the latest stable code. All changes from feature, release, and hotfix branches are eventually merged back into the master branch to keep it up to date.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	24	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Release Branch: Release branches are created to prepare code for delivery to customers. They are used for final testing and are isolated from active development to prevent new changes from affecting the release.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	25	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Hotfix Branch: Hotfix branches are created to address critical issues in production quickly. Changes made in hotfix branches are merged into both master and release branches to ensure the fix is included in all relevant versions.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	26	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Branching Strategy: A popular branching strategy involves using master/main, feature, release, and hotfix branches to organize development, testing, and delivery in software projects.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	27	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Branching Strategy in Git: Branching strategy is a method used by organizations to manage code changes, releases, and bug fixes in Git repositories. It involves creating and managing different branches for features, releases, and hotfixes to ensure smooth development and deployment processes.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	28	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git Repository Initialization and .git Directory: Initializing a Git repository creates a .git directory, which is essential for tracking changes, version control, and managing hooks to prevent sensitive information from being pushed.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	29	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git Add, Commit, and Version Control: Git add and commit are fundamental commands for tracking changes and maintaining version control. They allow developers to record changes, provide commit messages, and revert to previous versions if needed.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	30	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git Push and Remote Repositories: Git push is used to upload local changes to a remote repository, such as GitHub, Bitbucket, or self-hosted Git. Configuring a remote reference is necessary for push to work.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	31	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git Clone and Authentication Mechanisms: Git clone is used to copy remote repositories to the local machine. Authentication can be done via HTTPS, SSH, or GitHub CLI, requiring appropriate credentials.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	32	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Downloading Code Using Git (Clone and SSH): This knowledge point covers how to download code from repositories using Git, specifically via HTTPS and SSH methods, including authentication and key setup.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	33	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Difference Between Git Clone and Git Fork: Explains the distinction between cloning and forking in Git, including their use cases and implications in distributed version control systems.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	34	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git Branching and Its Purpose: Describes the concept of branching in Git, its purpose in development workflows, and how branches are used to isolate features and changes.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	35	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git Branch Creation and Workflow: Explains how to create branches in Git, add new features, and manage commits within branches.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	36	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Merging Branches in Git: Covers the process of merging branches in Git, including different methods such as merge, rebase, and cherry-pick, and how to resolve conflicts.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	37	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git Merge vs Git Rebase: Understanding the differences between git merge and git rebase, including their impact on commit history, workflow, and tracking changes in collaborative development environments.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	38	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Essential Git Commands and Interview Questions: Review of commonly used git commands and important git interview questions, including resources for further learning.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	39	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Deploying a Node.js Application on AWS EC2: Step-by-step process for deploying a Node.js application on AWS EC2, including repository cloning, environment variable setup, dependency installation, and running the application.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	40	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Learning Resources and Community Involvement: Recommendations for learning git and Node.js, including using official documentation, video tutorials, and community support.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	41	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
AWS IAM (Identity and Access Management): IAM is a service in AWS that allows you to manage access to AWS resources securely. It enables you to create users, assign roles, and set permissions so that only authorized users can access specific AWS services and resources.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	42	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
AWS EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud): EC2 is a service that provides scalable virtual servers in the cloud. It allows users to launch instances with various configurations, operating systems, and memory options, suitable for different application needs.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	43	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
SSH Authentication and Security: SSH (Secure Shell) is used to securely connect to remote servers. Authentication is managed using key pairs, and file permissions are set to restrict access to private keys.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	44	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
