\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 8. Distributed Version Control and Sharing Code\uc0\u8232 Gemini AI:\u8232 
\f1\b0 \'a0\uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 The title 
\f4\b "Distributed Version Control and Sharing Code"
\f1\b0  refers to the modern approach to managing and collaborating on software projects, with 
\f4\b Git
\f1\b0  being the most prominent example. It emphasizes a key advantage over older, centralized systems.\uc0\u8232 
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 Distributed Version Control 
\f14\b0 \uc0\u55356 \u57101 
\f1 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 Unlike a centralized system that relies on a single server, a 
\f4\b distributed version control system (DVCS)
\f1\b0  like Git gives every developer a 
\f4\b full copy of the entire repository
\f1\b0  on their local machine. This includes not just the latest version of the code, but also its complete history.\uc0\u8232 This design has several advantages:\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Offline Work
\f1\b0 : Since each developer has a full copy, they can work, commit, and manage versions even without an internet connection. They can sync their changes later.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Resilience
\f1\b0 : There is no single point of failure. If the main server goes down, teams can still collaborate by exchanging their local repositories, and the project's full history is preserved on every developer's machine.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Faster Operations
\f1\b0 : Most operations, like committing changes or viewing history, are performed on the local copy, making them significantly faster than having to communicate with a remote server for every action.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\'a0\uc0\u8232 
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 Sharing Code and Collaboration 
\f14\b0 \uc0\u55358 \u56605 
\f1 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 In a distributed model, sharing code with a team involves a few key steps and concepts:\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Remote Repositories
\f1\b0 : While a DVCS doesn't require a central server, teams almost always use one to simplify collaboration. These are called 
\f4\b remote repositories
\f1\b0  (e.g., a repository hosted on GitHub or GitLab).\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
git push
\f1\b0 : When a developer wants to share their local commits, they use the git push command to upload their changes to the remote repository.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
git pull
\f1\b0 : When a developer wants to get the latest changes that their teammates have pushed, they use the git pull command to download and merge those changes into their local repository.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Pull Requests (PRs)
\f1\b0 : On platforms like GitHub, the concept of a 
\f4\b Pull Request
\f1\b0  is central to collaboration. A PR is a request to merge changes from one branch to another. It provides a forum for code reviews, comments, and discussions before the changes are integrated into the main codebase.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
