\fs29\fsmilli14667 The diagram illustrates a common Git 
\f4\b branching strategy
\f1\b0  used in software development, often referred to as a 
\f4\b Git Flow
\f1\b0  model. The core idea is to separate different development efforts into distinct branches to ensure the stability of the main codebase.\uc0\u8232 The main concepts depicted are:\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
master / main Branch:
\f1\b0  This is the core, stable branch of the project. It represents the production-ready code. In the Uber analogy, this is the main, reliable service that customers use.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Feature Branches:
\f1\b0  These branches are created to develop new features without affecting the main branch. The diagram shows new features being developed (e.g., "Bikes" in the Uber example). Once a feature is complete and tested, it can be merged back into the main branch. The "Bikes" feature is eventually "Deleted" after its changes are integrated.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Release Branches:
\f1\b0  When the code for a new version is ready, a 
\f4\b release branch
\f1\b0  (e.g., "V2") is created from the main branch. This is where final testing, bug fixes, and last-minute changes are made before the new version is deployed to customers. This process ensures that the main branch remains untouched and stable while the new version is being finalized.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Hotfix Branches:
\f1\b0  The diagram shows a bug being reported by a "Customer" after a version has been released. A 
\f4\b hotfix branch
\f1\b0  is then created directly from the released code to apply an immediate fix. This fix is then merged back into both the main branch and the release branch to ensure the bug is resolved in all active versions.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
This strategy ensures that the main branch is always in a deployable state, while new features and fixes are developed and tested in isolated environments.\uc0\u8232 
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \uc0\u8232 Gemini AI:\u8232 
\f1\b0 \'a0\uc0\u8232 
\f4\b\fs29\fsmilli14667 Git branching strategies
\f1\b0  are conventions for how a development team uses branches to manage their project. A well-defined strategy helps teams collaborate effectively, manage code changes, and release new features predictably.\uc0\u8232 \'a0\u8232 
\f4\b\fs48 What is Branching?
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 A 
\f4\b branch
\f1\b0  is a lightweight, movable pointer to a commit. Think of it as a separate timeline of your project. When you create a branch, you're not making a copy of your entire repository; you're just creating a new pointer to a specific commit. This allows you to work on new features or bug fixes without affecting the main or stable codebase. Once your work is complete and tested, you can merge your branch back into the main branch.\uc0\u8232 \'a0\u8232 
\f4\b\fs48 Common Strategies
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 There are several popular branching strategies, each designed for a different type of workflow. The most common ones include:\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
GitFlow
\f1\b0 : This is a more formal and complex strategy that uses two main branches: main (for releases) and develop (for ongoing development). Developers create feature branches from develop, and when a feature is ready, it's merged back into develop. When it's time for a release, develop is merged into main, and a release branch is created. This strategy is great for projects with scheduled releases.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
GitHub Flow
\f1\b0 : This is a simpler, more modern strategy. It uses one main branch (typically called main or master) that is always in a deployable state. Developers create a new branch for every feature or bug fix. When they're ready, they open a 
\f4\b pull request
\f1\b0  (PR) to merge their branch into main. Once the PR is reviewed and approved, it's merged, and the change is deployed to production. This is ideal for continuous delivery.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
GitLab Flow
\f1\b0 : This strategy builds on GitHub Flow but adds a release branch and environment branches (e.g., production, staging) for more complex deployments. It's a good middle ground for teams that need more structure than GitHub Flow but don't require the full complexity of GitFlow.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
