Git Branching Strategy Explained
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 Git branching is a powerful feature that allows developers to work on different versions of a project simultaneously. A well-defined branching strategy helps teams manage development, releases, and bug fixes in a structured and predictable way. The most common types of branches are:\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Main/Trunk Branch:
\f1\b0  This is the primary branch of the repository, often called main or master. It always contains stable, production-ready code. All other branches are created from and merged back into this main branch. It serves as the single source of truth for the project.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Feature Branches:
\f1\b0  These are used to develop new features or significant changes. When a developer starts working on a new feature (e.g., a new login page or a new API endpoint), they create a new branch from main. This allows them to work on the feature in isolation without affecting the main codebase. Once the feature is complete and tested, the feature branch is merged back into main and then deleted.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Release Branches:
\f1\b0  When it's time to prepare a new version of the software for release, a release branch is created from main. This branch is used for final testing, bug fixes, and last-minute tweaks specific to that version. Once the release is ready, it's deployed, and the release branch is merged back into main and tagged with the version number (e.g., v1.0).\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Hotfix Branches:
\f1\b0  These are created to quickly address critical bugs in a production release. If a bug is found in the live version of the software, a hotfix branch is immediately created from the corresponding release branch (or from main if it's the latest version). The fix is applied to this branch and then merged back into both the main branch and any active release branches to ensure the fix is included everywhere. Hotfix branches are typically very short-lived.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
This structured approach prevents new, potentially unstable code from breaking the main codebase and ensures that the production version remains reliable. By using a branching strategy, teams can develop new features, prepare releases, and fix bugs without interfering with each other's work.\uc0\u8232 \'a0\u8232 \u8232 \u8232 Gemini AI:\u8232 \u8232 \'a0\u8232 The attached image is a diagram of a 
\f4\b Git branching strategy
\f1\b0  for a product like 
\f4\b Uber
\f1\b0 . It shows how different types of branches are used to manage features and releases, as well as a critical process called a "hotfix." The second image provides a written explanation of these concepts.\uc0\u8232 
