\f4\b Git Merge
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 git merge is a non-destructive operation that creates a new 
\f4\b merge commit
\f1\b0  to combine the histories of two branches. It preserves the exact history of both branches, resulting in a non-linear history that can be visualized as a fork and then a join.\uc0\u8232 
\f4\b How it works:
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
You move to the target branch (e.g., main).\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
You run git merge <branch-name>.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git takes all the changes from the <branch-name> and creates a new merge commit on the main branch. This new commit has two parent commits: the latest commit from main and the latest commit from the <branch-name>.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The original commits from the <branch-name> remain intact, preserving the branching structure.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
