\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 Git Rebase
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 git rebase rewrites commit history by moving a branch's commits to the end of another branch. It creates a linear history by "replaying" the commits from one branch onto another. This makes the project history cleaner and easier to read.\uc0\u8232 
\f4\b How it works:
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
You move to the feature branch (e.g., rebase-example).\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
You run git rebase <target-branch> (e.g., git rebase main).\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git "un-commits" all the changes from rebase-example, moves the branch's starting point to the latest commit of main, and then "re-commits" the changes from rebase-example on top.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
This creates a new, linear history where it appears as if the feature branch was created 
\f6\i after
\f1\i0  the latest changes on main.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
