\f4\b 7. Git Merge vs Git Rebase:
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f4\b Git Merge:
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \uc0\u8232 \'a0\u8232 \ul Gemini AI\ulnone :\uc0\u8232 Git merging is the process of combining two or more separate development histories into a single history. The image shows a 
\f4\b three-way merge
\f1\b0 , which is the most common type of merge. In this scenario, both the main branch and the feature branch have diverged since they last shared a commit.\uc0\u8232 \'a0\u8232 
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 Analogy: Merging Two Recipes
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 Imagine you and a friend are working on a collaborative cookbook. You start with a basic cookie recipe.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
You 
\f4\b fork
\f1\b0  your own copy of the recipe and add your own twist, like extra chocolate chips. 
\f14 \uc0\u55356 \u57195 
\f1 \
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
At the same time, your friend 
\f4\b forks
\f1\b0  their own copy and adds their twist, like crushed walnuts. 
\f14 \uc0\u55356 \u57194 
\f1 \
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
When it's time to create the final recipe for the cookbook, you can't simply take either your version or your friend's version, because you'd lose the other person's changes.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Instead, you 
\f4\b merge
\f1\b0  your recipes. You take both versions, combine the unique changes (the chocolate chips and the walnuts), and write down a new, final recipe. This new recipe is the 
\f4\b merge commit
\f1\b0 . It combines all the changes while keeping a record of both original recipes.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The image shows this same process: the main branch (blue) and the feature branch (green) each have their own separate commits. The merge commit (the star) is a new commit that combines both histories, with two "parents"\'97the latest commit from the main branch and the latest commit from the feature branch. This preserves the history of both branches, creating a clear record of when they were joined.\uc0\u8232 \'a0\u8232 You can learn more about how merges work by watching {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=10PLCbsdXVI"}}{\fldrslt \cf8 \ul \ulc8 What is a Merge Commit in Git?}}.\uc0\u8232 
\fs42\fsmilli21333 \'a0\uc0\u8232 
\f4\b Git Rebase:
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \uc0\u8232 \'a0\u8232 
\f4\b Gemini AI:
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 git rebase is a Git command that integrates changes from one branch into another by moving or "replaying" commits. Unlike git merge, which combines two histories, rebase rewrites history to create a clean, linear sequence of commits. The image shows the process of rebasing a feature branch onto a main branch.\u8232 
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 Analogy: Reorganizing a Story
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 Imagine you're writing a story with a friend. The main branch is the core plot of the story, and your feature branch contains a new subplot you've been working on.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
While you were writing your subplot, your friend added a new chapter to the main story.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Now, you want to integrate your subplot into the main story, but you want it to feel seamless, as if you wrote your chapters after your friend's latest one.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Rebasing
\f1\b0  is like taking your chapters, moving them to the end of your friend's latest chapter, and then rewriting their "parent" or "starting point" to be the end of the main branch.
\f4\b \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f1\b0 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The final result is a single, clean story where all the new chapters appear in a logical order, one after the other. It looks as if the subplot was always written after the latest changes in the main story.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The diagram illustrates this: the green commits from the feature branch are lifted and "replayed" on top of the blue commits from the main branch. This creates a new, linear history, making the project's log much cleaner and easier to read than a merge, which would have created a new, separate merge commit.\uc0\u8232 
\f4\b \uc0\u8232 \u8232 Explanation:
\f1\b0  Both merge and rebase integrate changes. The key difference is how they handle the commit history:\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
git merge
\f1\b0  creates a new "merge commit" that explicitly shows the history of both branches joining together. It preserves the history as it happened.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
git rebase
\f1\b0  moves the commits from one branch and reapplies them on top of another, creating a cleaner, linear history. It rewrites history.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy:
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx1660\tx2160\pardeftab720\li2160\fi-2160\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl2
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
git merge:
\f1\b0  Merging is like 
\f4\b filing a report on a team meeting
\f1\b0 . The report explicitly mentions that a meeting occurred to combine everyone's work.\
\ls290\ilvl2
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
git rebase:
\f1\b0  Rebasing is like 
\f4\b editing a historical timeline
\f1\b0 . You take all the new events from one timeline and place them at the end of another, making it look like they happened in a straight line, without a separate "merging event."\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Example:
\f1\b0  A developer uses git merge to integrate a team's changes, ensuring the history of everyone's work is visible. They use git rebase on a personal branch to clean up a messy history before pushing it to a public repository.\
