Explanation:
\f1\b0  This is a reminder to review common Git commands and be prepared to answer interview questions about them. Commands like git log, git status, git diff, and the difference between merge and rebase are common topics.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy:
\f1\b0  This is 
\f4\b studying for an exam
\f1\b0  on Git. You practice the most common commands and review key concepts to be prepared for the test.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Example:
\f1\b0  An interviewer might ask, "What is the difference between git pull and git fetch?" or "How would you revert a specific commit?"\uc0\u8232 \ul Gemini AI:\ulnone \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
git log: Shows the commit history.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
git status: Shows the state of the working directory and staging area.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
git diff: Shows changes between commits, a commit and the working directory, etc.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Merge vs. Rebase:
\f1\b0  git merge combines branches and preserves history with a merge commit, while git rebase rewrites history to create a clean, linear commit log.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\ul Questions:\ulnone \uc0\u8232 \'a0\u8232 An interviewer might ask, "What is the difference between git pull and git fetch?" or "How would you revert a specific commit?"\u8232 git pull and git fetch are both used to retrieve changes from a remote repository, but they do so differently. git fetch downloads the changes to your local repository without automatically merging them into your working branch, giving you a chance to review them first. git pull is a combination of git fetch and git merge, which means it downloads the changes and immediately applies them to your current branch, which can sometimes lead to conflicts.\u8232 You would revert a specific commit using the 
\f4\b git revert
\f1\b0  command. This command is the safest way to undo a commit because it creates a new commit that reverses the changes of the specified commit. This means the original commit remains in the history, and the new "revert" commit documents that a change was undone. This is crucial for shared branches, as it avoids rewriting history that other team members may have already based their work on.\uc0\u8232 To revert a commit:\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Use git log to find the commit hash (the unique ID) of the commit you want to undo.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Run git revert <commit_hash>.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git will create a new commit that undoes the changes. You'll be prompted to edit the commit message.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Once the new commit is created locally, you can push it to the remote repository.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
git reset is another way to undo commits, but it should be used with caution, especially on shared branches, because it rewrites commit history by moving the branch pointer back to a previous commit and deleting all subsequent commits. \uc0\u8232 This video explains the practical difference between git pull and git fetch by showing how each command affects the files on your local machine. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GOrhB6eYASU"}}{\fldrslt \cf8 \ul \ulc8 Git Fetch vs Git Pull? Which one should you choose?}}\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \'a0\u8232 \'a0\u8232 \'a0\u8232 =================================\u8232 \'a0\u8232 
