37. Git Merge vs Git Rebase
\f1\b0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Key Points
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx1660\tx2160\pardeftab720\li2160\fi-2160\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl2\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git merge and git rebase both integrate changes from one branch into another, but they organize commit history differently.\
\ls290\ilvl2\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git merge combines branches but does not maintain a linear commit history; changes may be harder to track in sequence.\
\ls290\ilvl2\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Git rebase applies commits from one branch onto another in a linear fashion, making the commit history easier to follow.\
\ls290\ilvl2\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
In large projects, git rebase is preferred for tracking changes and maintaining a clear, linear commit history.\
\ls290\ilvl2\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Developers may choose merge if they are not concerned about linear history.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Explanation\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 The class used diagrams to show the main branch and how merge and rebase affect commit history. With merge, changes are updated at the top, and reading is updated at the bottom before the branch creation. This can make tracking changes difficult for developers, as the commit history is not linear. With rebase, all commits from the main branch are applied to the rebase branch, resulting in a linear commit history. For example, if there are 10 commits in the main branch, after rebase, all 10 commits will be available in the rebase branch. This makes it easier to understand the sequence of changes. The instructor recommends using rebase for large projects where tracking changes is important, and merge when linear history is not a priority.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Example: Tracking Changes with Merge vs Rebase\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 A developer creates a merge branch from the main branch. After merging, the changes are updated at the top, and reading is updated at the bottom before the branch creation. This makes it hard to track changes linearly. With rebase, the developer creates a rebase branch from the main branch. All commits from the main branch (e.g., 10 commits) are applied to the rebase branch, resulting in a linear commit history.\
\pard\tx1660\tx2160\pardeftab720\li2160\fi-2160\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl2\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Step 1: Create a merge branch from the main branch.\
\ls290\ilvl2\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Step 2: Merge the branch; changes are not in linear order.\
\ls290\ilvl2\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Step 3: Create a rebase branch from the main branch.\
\ls290\ilvl2\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Step 4: Rebase applies all main branch commits to the rebase branch, maintaining linear history.\
