\ls290\ilvl2\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
IAM allows creation of users and assignment of roles.\
\ls290\ilvl2\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Root account has full access; best practice is to create separate users for team members.\
\ls290\ilvl2\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Roles and permissions can be customized for each user or group.\
\ls290\ilvl2\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Permissions can be added or deleted later by modifying policies.\
\ls290\ilvl2\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f8 \uc0\u9702 
\f1 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Tags can be used to identify resources associated with users.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Explanation\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 In an organization, the root account is the admin user with access to all AWS services. However, for security and management, it is recommended to create individual IAM users for team members and assign them roles with specific permissions. For example, a developer working on authentication may only need access to certain services, while another may need access to EC2. IAM allows you to restrict access, preventing users from accidentally deleting resources or accessing services they are not familiar with. Permissions can be managed via policies, which can be modified at any time. Users can be grouped, and permissions can be assigned to groups for easier management.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Creating an IAM User with Administrator Access\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 A new IAM user is created by going to the IAM console, clicking 'Add user', assigning a username, and setting a custom password. Permissions are set by attaching policies, such as 'AdministratorAccess'. The user can be added to a group with predefined permissions. After creation, the user can log in using the IAM sign-in link, account ID, and username.\
\pard\tx1660\tx2160\pardeftab720\li2160\fi-2160\partightenfactor0
