Explanation\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 EC2 allows users to set up remote servers, which is useful when local machines lack sufficient resources. For example, running Kubernetes with Minikube requires significant memory, which may not be available on a laptop. EC2 instances can be launched with different OS images and configurations. The smallest instance type is T2 nano, followed by T2 micro, T2 small, and T2 medium. AWS provides a free tier for beginners to learn without incurring costs. Key pairs (.pem files) are used for secure SSH access. Instances are assigned public IP addresses and can be launched in different availability zones to minimize latency. Maintenance overhead is reduced as AWS handles patching and updates.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Launching an EC2 Instance with Ubuntu 2022.04 LTS\uc0\u8232 
\f1\b0 Go to EC2 console, click 'Launch Instances', enter instance name, select OS image (Ubuntu 2022.04 LTS), choose instance type (T2 micro for free tier), create a new key pair (.pem file), allow SSH from anywhere, and launch the instance. The instance is assigned an instance ID and public IP address. The instance is launched in the North Virginia region.\
