\ls290\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
2. How to create EC2 Instance ? What are some of the good practices ? \uc0\u8232 3. How to access the EC2 Instance ? \u8232 4. Deploy an application on to AWS EC2 ? \u8232 5. Expose the application to outside world ? \u8232 6. Access the application deployed on AWS from your laptop.\u8232 \u8232 \'a0\u8232 Here's a guide on how to perform the essential steps to deploy and expose an application on an EC2 instance, framed for an interview context.\u8232 
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 1. Create an IAM User and Log In
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 To create a new 
\f4\b IAM user
\f1\b0  (Identity and Access Management), you log in to the AWS Management Console with the root account and navigate to the IAM dashboard. You create a new user, specify their username, and set a password for console access. The most crucial step is to attach policies to this user. This is a best practice called the 
\f4\b Principle of Least Privilege
\f1\b0 , which means you grant the user only the permissions required to do their job, such as launching an EC2 instance, instead of giving them full administrative access. Once created, you log out of the root account and log back in using the new IAM user credentials.\uc0\u8232 \'a0\u8232 
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 2. How to Create an EC2 Instance and Best Practices
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 You create a new EC2 instance from the AWS console. The key steps and best practices are:\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Choose an AMI:
\f1\b0  An Amazon Machine Image (AMI) is a template for your instance's operating system and pre-installed software. You select an AMI that suits your application needs, like an Amazon Linux or Ubuntu image.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Select an Instance Type:
\f1\b0  This determines the CPU, memory, and storage capacity of your instance. For a simple app, a 
\f4\b t2.micro
\f1\b0  is a good, cost-effective choice as it's often covered by the AWS Free Tier.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Create a Key Pair:
\f1\b0  A key pair is essential for securely connecting to your instance. You create a new key pair, which generates a public key on AWS and a private key file (.pem) for you to download. You must store this private key securely.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Configure a Security Group:
\f1\b0  This acts as a virtual firewall. You must create rules to allow inbound traffic, such as 
\f4\b SSH
\f1\b0  on port 22 for secure access from your IP and 
\f4\b HTTP
\f1\b0  on port 80 to allow web traffic from the outside world. This is a critical step for exposing your application later.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\'a0\uc0\u8232 
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 3. How to Access the EC2 Instance
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 You can access your EC2 instance using 
\f4\b SSH (Secure Shell)
\f1\b0  from your local machine's terminal.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
First, you navigate to the directory where you saved your private key file.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
You must change the permissions of the private key file to ensure it's not publicly accessible by running chmod 400 <your-key-name.pem>.\
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Then, you connect to the instance using the SSH command: ssh -i <your-key-name.pem> ec2-user@<instance-public-ip>. The ec2-user is the default username for Amazon Linux AMIs.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\'a0\uc0\u8232 
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 4. Deploy an Application
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 Once you've connected via SSH, you can deploy your application. This typically involves:
\f4\b \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Installing dependencies:
\f1\b0  You'll install any necessary software, such as a web server (like Nginx or Apache), a runtime (like Node.js), or a database.
\f4\b \
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Cloning the code:
\f1\b0  You use git to clone your application's source code from a repository (e.g., GitHub).
\f4\b \
\ls290\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Running the application:
\f1\b0  You start the application on the server, often using a command like npm start, python app.py, or similar, depending on the application's language.
\f4\b \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\'a0\uc0\u8232 
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 5. Expose the Application to the Outside World
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 You expose the application to the internet by ensuring the 
\f4\b security group
\f1\b0  you created has an inbound rule allowing 
\f4\b HTTP traffic on port 80
\f1\b0  from all IP addresses (0.0.0.0/0). This allows users to access your web application using the EC2 instance's public IP address.\uc0\u8232 \'a0\u8232 
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 6. Access the Application from Your Laptop
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\fs29\fsmilli14667 To access the deployed application, you simply open a web browser on your laptop and navigate to the public IP address of your EC2 instance. The browser sends a request, which is allowed by the security group, and the web server on your instance serves the application's content back to you.\uc0\u8232 The video below explains how to create an AWS account, which is the first step before performing any of the tasks mentioned above. It is a good starting point for anyone who is new to AWS. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.google.com/search?q=https://www.youtube.com/watch%3Fv%3D1Eua7J6ExUo"}}{\fldrslt \cf8 \ul \ulc8 How to Create AWS Account?}}\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \'a0\u8232 
