Explanation:
\f1\b0  Git branching creates a separate line of development from the main codebase. It allows you to work on new features or bug fixes in isolation without affecting the stable version of the code. Once a branch is complete, it can be merged back into the main branch.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy:
\f1\b0  An 
\f4\b artist's canvas
\f1\b0 . You start with a main painting (the main branch), but when you want to experiment with a new technique, you get a new, separate canvas (a new branch) to work on. If the experiment fails, you can simply throw away the new canvas without ruining the original painting.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Example:
\f1\b0  Before adding a new login feature, you create a new branch with git checkout -b login-feature. All of your code changes for that feature are contained within this branch.\
