Explanation:
\f1\b0  Merging is the process of integrating changes from one branch into another. The git merge command is used to combine divergent codebases back together. A key part of merging is resolving any conflicts that arise when the same lines of code have been changed in both branches.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy:
\f1\b0  Merging is like 
\f4\b joining two different railroad tracks into a single one
\f1\b0 . The process involves making sure the tracks line up and a train can pass smoothly. If the tracks don't line up perfectly (a conflict), you must fix them before the train can proceed.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Example:
\f1\b0  A developer has been working on a new login feature on a branch named login-feature. The team lead runs git checkout main to switch to the main branch and then git merge login-feature to bring the new login code into the main codebase. If another developer had made a change to the same file, a conflict would arise and have to be manually resolved.\
