37. Git Merge vs Git Rebase
\f1\b0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Explanation:
\f1\b0  Both merge and rebase integrate changes, but they do so in fundamentally different ways that affect the commit history.\
\pard\tx1660\tx2160\pardeftab720\li2160\fi-2160\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl2
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
git merge
\f1\b0  creates a new "merge commit" that explicitly shows the history of the two branches joining together. It preserves the history exactly as it happened.\
\ls290\ilvl2
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
git rebase
\f1\b0  moves the commits from one branch and reapplies them on top of another, creating a cleaner, linear history. It rewrites the history, making it look as if all the changes happened in a single, straight line.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy:
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx1660\tx2160\pardeftab720\li2160\fi-2160\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl2
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
git merge
\f1\b0  is like 
\f4\b filing a report on a team meeting
\f1\b0 . The report explicitly mentions that a meeting occurred to combine everyone's work.\
\ls290\ilvl2
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
git rebase
\f1\b0  is like 
\f4\b editing a historical timeline
\f1\b0 . You take all the new events from one timeline and place them at the end of another, making it look like they happened in a single, straight line, without a separate "merging event."\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Example:
\f1\b0  A developer needs to update their feature branch with the latest changes from the main branch. They can use git merge main on their feature branch, which will create a merge commit. Alternatively, they can use git rebase main on their feature branch, which will replay their commits on top of main, resulting in a cleaner commit history.\
