43. SSH Authentication and Security
\f1\b0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Explanation:
\f1\b0  SSH (Secure Shell) is a cryptographic network protocol used to securely connect to remote servers. It uses key pairs (a public key on the server and a private key on the client) to provide strong, encrypted authentication without a password, significantly reducing the risk of a security breach.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy:
\f1\b0  A 
\f4\b secret handshake and a key
\f1\b0  to a private club. Only those who know the secret handshake (the private key) and have been approved beforehand (public key on the server) are allowed in.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Example:
\f1\b0  You use an SSH client like PuTTY or the built-in terminal on macOS/Linux to connect to your EC2 instance using the command ssh -i my-key.pem ec2-user@<instance-ip>.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl0
