46. Environment Variables and Application Configuration
\f1\b0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Explanation:
\f1\b0  Environment variables are used to store sensitive information (like API keys and passwords) and application settings. It's a best practice to keep this information separate from the code and load it at runtime, as it prevents credentials from being exposed in public repositories.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy:
\f1\b0  A 
\f4\b hidden key for a house
\f1\b0 . Instead of sewing the key into the blueprint, you hide it outside in a secure place. The construction workers know where to find the key to get into the house, but it's not exposed in the public design.\
\ls290\ilvl1
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Example:
\f1\b0  Instead of hard-coding an API key in your Node.js code, you would use process.env.STRIPE_API_KEY and set the environment variable on your EC2 instance before starting the application.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls290\ilvl0
