Step-by-Step Deployment on AWS
\f1\b0 \
\ls292\ilvl0
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Kunal takes over and walks viewers through the entire deployment process. He starts with the application's GitHub repository, which he encourages everyone to use as a guide. The steps are:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Clone the repository:
\f1\b0  Kunal uses the git clone command to copy the code from GitHub to his local machine. He emphasizes the importance of learning basic Git commands for anyone in software development.
\f4\b \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy: Cloning a repository is like getting a copy of a recipe book from a digital library to your personal bookshelf.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Set up the local environment:
\f1\b0  The application requires environment variables for credentials (like a Stripe API key). Kunal creates a .env file to store these, explaining that this is a best practice to keep sensitive information out of the public code.
\f4\b \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy: The .env file is like a private notebook for your secret recipe ingredients. You don't write them directly in the recipe book that everyone can see.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Install dependencies and run the app locally:
\f1\b0  He uses npm install to download all the necessary packages and npm run start to get the application running on his laptop. This step is a crucial test to ensure the application works before attempting to deploy it on a server.
\f4\b \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy: This is like gathering all your ingredients and tools and trying the recipe in your own kitchen first to make sure it tastes right before serving it to others.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\'a0\
\ls292\ilvl0
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Deploying to the Cloud
\f1\b0 \
\ls292\ilvl0
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Once the app is verified locally, the video moves on to deploying it on 
\f4\b Amazon Web Services (AWS)
\f1\b0 .\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM):
\f1\b0  Kunal starts by explaining 
\f4\b IAM
\f1\b0 , a service that lets you manage user permissions and access to AWS resources. He demonstrates how to create a new user with limited access, a crucial security best practice to avoid using the powerful root account for daily tasks.
\f4\b \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy: IAM is like an office manager who gives different employees keys to only the rooms they need access to, preventing them from entering sensitive areas like the finance department.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Launching an EC2 Instance:
\f1\b0  Kunal shows how to create an 
\f4\b EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud)
\f1\b0  instance, which is essentially a virtual server in the cloud. He chooses an Ubuntu operating system and a T2 micro instance type, which is available on the free tier for new users. He also generates a 
\f4\b key pair
\f1\b0 , a secure file needed to log in.
\f4\b \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy: An EC2 instance is like renting a powerful, new computer in the cloud. You don\'92t need to buy it or maintain it yourself; you just use it as needed. The key pair is the special key that proves you're the one who rented it and allows you to log in securely.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Connecting and Setting Up the Instance:
\f1\b0  He uses the key pair and SSH to securely connect to the new virtual server from his terminal. He then repeats the initial steps of installing Node.js and the application\'92s dependencies, this time on the remote server.
\f4\b \
\ls292\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Exposing the Application (The "Magic" Step):
\f1\b0  After running the app, it's not immediately accessible from the internet. Kunal explains that the virtual server's port (3000 in this case) needs to be exposed. He goes into the 
\f4\b security groups
\f1\b0  settings for the EC2 instance and adds an 
\f4\b inbound rule
\f1\b0  to allow traffic on port 3000 from anywhere on the internet.
\f4\b \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f5 \uc0\u9702 
\f4 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Analogy: This is like having a private party inside your house. Even if the music is playing, no one outside can join unless you open the door. The security group rule is the equivalent of opening that door for a specific port.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl0
\f1\b0 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\'a0\
\ls292\ilvl0
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Conclusion and Call to Action
\f1\b0 \
\ls292\ilvl0
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
With the inbound rule set, the application becomes live and accessible via the EC2 instance's public IP address. Both Abhishek and Kunal celebrate the successful deployment, encouraging viewers to try it themselves using the provided GitHub repository. They wrap up the video by inviting viewers to ask questions in the comments and to thank Kunal on his LinkedIn for his efforts. They also confirm that because the IP address is public and the security rule allows access from "anywhere," the application can be accessed from any computer in the world.\
