=====================================================================================\
\ls292\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\'a0\
\ls292\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
You've asked about the complete process of setting up and accessing an application on AWS. This involves several key steps, from creating the user to making the application available to the public. Here's a clear and direct breakdown.\
\ls292\ilvl0
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
1. How to create an IAM USER and log in
\f1\b0 \
\ls292\ilvl0
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The best practice for using AWS is to avoid using the root user of your account. Instead, you should create an 
\f4\b IAM (Identity and Access Management)
\f1\b0  user with specific, limited permissions.\
\ls292\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
To do this, log into the AWS Management Console as the root user, navigate to the IAM dashboard, and create a new user. You'll give the user a name and choose the access type (console access, programmatic access, or both). The most important step is to assign a policy to the user or add the user to a group with a policy attached. For a new user, you might start with a policy like AdministratorAccess and then refine it later to follow the principle of least privilege. After creating the user, you'll receive a unique sign-in URL, username, and password.\
\ls292\ilvl0
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
2. How to create an EC2 Instance
\f1\b0 \
\ls292\ilvl0
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
An 
\f4\b EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud)
\f1\b0  instance is a virtual server in the cloud. When creating one, a few good practices will help ensure a secure and stable environment.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl0
\f4\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Choose an AMI
\f1\b0 : An Amazon Machine Image (AMI) is a template for your instance's operating system. For a new project, a free-tier eligible AMI like 
\f4\b Ubuntu Server
\f1\b0  or 
\f4\b Amazon Linux 2
\f1\b0  is a great starting point.\
\ls292\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Select an Instance Type
\f1\b0 : The instance type determines the hardware of your virtual server. The 
\f4\b t2.micro
\f1\b0  instance is free-tier eligible and suitable for most small applications.\
\ls292\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Create a Key Pair
\f1\b0 : A key pair is essential for securely connecting to your instance. You'll download a .pem file that contains your private key. Make sure to save this file in a secure location on your computer.\
\ls292\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Configure a Security Group
\f1\b0 : A security group acts as a virtual firewall. It's a best practice to configure inbound rules to only allow traffic on the ports your application needs, and from trusted IP addresses. For example, you should allow SSH traffic (port 22) only from your IP address.\
\ls292\ilvl0
\f4\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Add Tags
\f1\b0 : Use tags, like a Name tag, to easily identify and manage your instance.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl0
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
3. How to access the EC2 Instance
\f1\b0 \
\ls292\ilvl0
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The most common way to access a Linux EC2 instance is with 
\f4\b SSH (Secure Shell)
\f1\b0  from your local machine's terminal. To connect, you'll need the private key file you downloaded earlier and the instance's public IP address.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
First, set the correct permissions for your key file. The command chmod 400 your-key-pair.pem ensures only you can read it.\
\ls292\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Then, use the following command to connect, replacing the placeholder values with your own: ssh -i "your-key-pair.pem" ec2-user@your-instance-public-ip\
\ls292\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The username (ec2-user, ubuntu, etc.) depends on the AMI you chose.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl0
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
4. Deploy an application on an EC2 Instance
\f1\b0 \
\ls292\ilvl0
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
There are many ways to deploy an application, but a simple, manual approach involves the following steps:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Connect to your EC2 instance using SSH.\
\ls292\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Install any necessary software dependencies, such as a web server (like Nginx or Apache), or a programming language runtime (like Python).\
\ls292\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Transfer your application files to the instance. You can do this with the scp command or by cloning a Git repository.\
\ls292\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Run your application's startup command to get it running on the server.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\ls292\ilvl0
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
5. Expose the application to the outside world
\f1\b0 \
\ls292\ilvl0
\fs29\fsmilli14667 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Even if your application is running on your EC2 instance, it won't be accessible to the public by default. To expose it, you need to open the specific port your application is running on in the instance's security group.\
\ls292\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
For example, if your application is a web server running on port 8000, you would add a new inbound rule to your security group to allow traffic on port 8000. For a public-facing application, you would allow this traffic from 0.0.0.0/0, which means anyone can access it.\
\ls292\ilvl0
\f4\b\fs42\fsmilli21333 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
6. Access the application deployed on AWS from your laptop
\f1\b0 \
\ls292\ilvl0
