\f4\b\fs53\fsmilli26667 \cf13 Day 12 | Deploy and expose your First App to AWS | Feat. Kunal Verma | Live Project |\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/hashtag/aws"}}{\fldrslt \cf8 \ul \ulc8 #aws}}\'a0projects
\f1\b0 \cf0 \

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \uc0\u8232 \'a0
\f0\fs24 \cf18 To prepare for a real-time interview, you can use the 
\f2\b STAR (Situation, Task, Action, Result)
\f0\b0  method to demonstrate your practical expertise with AWS deployments and security. Based on the walkthrough from Abhishek and Kunal, here are the top real-time questions and scenarios.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf19 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf18 1. Scenario: Cloud Security & Access Management\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf18 Question:
\f0\b0  
\f3\i "How do you manage secure access to AWS resources in a multi-user environment?"
\f0\i0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls293\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf18 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
S (Situation):
\f0\b0  My team was managing a production environment where several developers needed to deploy updates, but using the root account for daily tasks posed a significant security risk.\
\ls293\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
T (Task):
\f0\b0  I needed to implement a secure access model that followed the 
\f2\b Principle of Least Privilege
\f0\b0 .\
\ls293\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A (Action):
\f0\b0  I utilized 
\f2\b AWS IAM
\f0\b0  to create individual user accounts rather than sharing root credentials. I assigned specific 
\f2\b policies and groups
\f0\b0 \'97for example, granting developers access only to EC2 and not to billing or S3. I also ensured that administrative access was limited to only the necessary lead engineers.\
\ls293\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
R (Result):
\f0\b0  This centralized access management reduced the risk of accidental resource deletion and improved our security audit trail, as every action could be traced back to a specific IAM user.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf19 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf18 2. Scenario: Troubleshooting Application Connectivity\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf18 Question:
\f0\b0  
\f3\i "Tell me about a time you deployed an application but couldn't access it externally. How did you resolve it?"
\f0\i0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls294\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf18 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
S (Situation):
\f0\b0  After successfully deploying a Node.js application to an 
\f2\b AWS EC2 instance
\f0\b0 , the application was running perfectly on the server (Port 3000), but I could not reach it through the public IP address.\
\ls294\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
T (Task):
\f0\b0  I had to identify the "bottleneck" preventing the internet from communicating with my cloud server.\
\ls294\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A (Action):
\f0\b0  I diagnosed the issue as a 
\f2\b Security Group
\f0\b0  restriction. I navigated to the instance's security settings and added an 
\f2\b Inbound Rule
\f0\b0  to explicitly allow traffic on 
\f2\b Port 3000
\f0\b0  from "Anywhere" (0.0.0.0/0). I also verified that Port 22 was open so I could continue managing the server via 
\f2\b SSH
\f0\b0 .\
\ls294\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
R (Result):
\f0\b0  The application became instantly accessible to the public. I subsequently documented the required ports in our deployment guide to ensure future builds were "exposed" correctly from day one.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf19 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf18 3. Scenario: Environment Configuration & Security\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf18 Question:
\f0\b0  
\f3\i "How do you handle sensitive information like API keys in your deployment pipeline?"
\f0\i0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls295\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf18 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
S (Situation):
\f0\b0  For a payment-integrated application, I had to manage sensitive credentials like 
\f2\b Stripe API keys
\f0\b0 .\
\ls295\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
T (Task):
\f0\b0  My goal was to prevent these secrets from being hardcoded into the source code or accidentally pushed to a public GitHub repository.\
\ls295\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
A (Action):
\f0\b0  I implemented an 
\f2\b environment variable
\f0\b0  strategy using a 
\f2\b .env file
\f0\b0 . I used this file to store the credentials locally and on the EC2 server, then configured the application to pull these values at runtime. I also ensured the \cf20 \cb21 .env\cf18 \cb1  file was added to \cf20 \cb21 .gitignore\cf18 \cb1  so it remained a "hidden" and private file.\
\ls295\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
R (Result):
\f0\b0  This approach allowed us to securely scale the application and switch between "Test" and "Production" API keys without changing a single line of the main application code.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf19 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf18 Interview "Cheat Sheet" for AWS Deployments:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa200\partightenfactor0
\ls296\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf18 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
EC2 Connection:
\f0\b0  Use \cf20 \cb21 ssh -i "key.pem" user@ip\cf18 \cb1 . Ensure permissions are set to \cf20 \cb21 400\cf18 \cb1  so the key isn't "too open".\
\ls296\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Node.js Setup:
\f0\b0  On a fresh Ubuntu instance, always run \cf20 \cb21 sudo apt update\cf18 \cb1  before installing \cf20 \cb21 nodejs\cf18 \cb1  and \cf20 \cb21 npm\cf18 \cb1 .\
\ls296\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Verification:
\f0\b0  Use \cf20 \cb21 npm run start\cf18 \cb1  to test the server locally before going live.\
\ls296\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Global Access:
\f0\b0  Setting an inbound rule to \cf20 \cb21 0.0.0.0/0\cf18 \cb1  makes the app accessible from any computer in the world.\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\sa200\partightenfactor0

